\f1 Prologue\par
\b0 Nicholls County, Missouri, was organized  on January 29, 1841 as Plutarch County.  The name was changed after the Civil War by petition from the residents to rename it after Samuel Nicholas, the first Commandant of the Marine Corps.  The town had been settled by Marine veterans of the conflict from both sides who wanted to live together as brother Marines once again.  Attempts to correct the spelling error by the town and county were  made during the 1890s, but by that time it was well known as Nicholls and they had already been allowed one name change.  This remained as a source of contention up to the time of this story, withh a few people still attempting the change every year.  Since the 1920s it had been a routine vote-down annually at city meetings.  No one knows who made the initial error - the state claims the county submitted it as Nicholls, and the county hotly denied doing so. The original paperwork seems to have gone missing.  \par
The original town of Plutarchville was completely burned under General Order Number 11.  Under that order the counties bordering Kansas were evacuated.  Among the evacuees was the Mueller family, which had \lang1033 acquired the west half of then-Plutarch County sometime before the war. They farmed and ranched, not too successfully, up to evacuation. A letter from an Augustus Mueller (the name is indecipherable - it could be Miller or Mohler or other variations) to his brother Otto in Kansas City was handed over to Nicholls County for historical purposes after the death of Otto in 1884.  The letter, in German, related how they were actually glad to get off the land, as the soil was poor, and they were reluctant at the prospect of returning, but 'all their wealth was sunk into the land.'  That phrase has caused a great deal of comment.  The letter is undated and there is no envelope.  Some think it might be a fraud. \b\lang9\par

\pard\b0\lang1033 After the Civil War the family began rebuilding their burned-out ranch. After the events in Harrisonville related below, Mrs. Mueller took her children to live with her sister in Minnesota and abandoned the land.  There were no buyers -  the land here was not very productive for farming or ranching. While one notorious wooded ravine seemed to flourish, the land around it was parched for miles, almost soilless even past the area that would become the POW camp.  East of the woods the ravine emptied out onto flat land.  A spring fed very shallow, algae covered rocks where dragonflies danced and mosquitoes hunted, but the water was too shallow for anything but insects.  There were a few pools but they were also shallow and far between and reeked. Westward from those woods no trees grew for miles until  the soil slowly returned to normal prairie.\par
\par
To the eye the land looked completely flat, somehow barren wasteland, but there were rolling prairie hills with cottonwoods, black locusts and Osage oranges clinging to the shallow creekbeds of stagnant, intermittent pools and rotting wood from felled trees, overseen in wet weather by biting flies.  Rumor was that the Indians had passed quickly through the area if they had to, and the only fertile ravine was avoided by them.  \par
\par
From late 1942 to 1946 the deserted Mueller Ranch housed Camp Nicholls, a POW camp for Italian officers on a leveled-out area over a mile long and over half a mile wide that went down into bedrock for much of its length. The POWs, many of whom were musicians, organized their own orchestra and to the bewilderment of the townspeople of Nicholls, gave concerts that could be heard in Nicholls. A professor of history there gave a series of lectures that were well-received at the Epper Church.  Nicholls was ambivalent about them.   In 1944 Camp Nicholls was repurposed for German enlisted personnel and officers deemed dangerous:  the new orientation and officer corps was more disciplinary: among the inmates were hard-core Nazis and soldiers who had attempted to escape, assaulted guards or fellow inmates. The music stopped.  The camp underwent a sea-change, and even the guards were changed.  The later prisoners were taken directly to the camp and confined, and the guards never mingled in town. \par
\par
The strange, persistent rumor of treasure was in the air.  They were set to finding the treasure, and anywhere there was soil was a place they dug up.  They dug a quarry by hand, breaking rock that was removed and used elsewhere by the Army.  The soil was left in mounds or blew away.  \par
\par
The POW camp quarried high quality limestone on its western edge, first to produce stone, later more as a disciplinary incentive. The Italians built a beautiful stone chapel as well as a few small walls. They had had their own priest, in itself more of a cause of suspicion for Protestant Nicholls than that the US was at war with Italy.   During the German internment the rock was mainly used as gravel to widen the field of fire around the camp. The army razed most of the camp after the war, pushing the buildings into large piles, burning them. and pushing the still-smoking debris into the quarry, where it smoldered for years. A few better-built buildings remained, including the camp headquarters, the infirmary and a stone chapel the Italians had lovingly constructed. \par
\par
All prisoners were repatriated in 1946, directly moved from the camp to the train station still under guard. They repatriated the dead as well, and the graves were filled with gravel.  \par
\par
After the war a Don Rafael of the Benedictines, who had been interred in Camp Nicholls as a private, expressed interest in the land.  He said that land that had once been a prison would be a fine place to find true liberty.  He had, he said, awoken to his Catholic faith and his call to the Benedictine order on the property.  The church in Italy sent him and some other monks to the land here with the blessing of the local diocese, under the guidance of Conception Abbey in northwest Missouri, and American Benedictine monks from there joined them.  The army handed the 40 acres or so of their property over to the Benedictines after the war as the Muellers could not then be found, according to some, or refused to accept the land back, according to others. The monks converted the few remaining buildings into a Retreat Center.  The stone chapel remained.  With maintenance issues, declining interest in it and better facilities elsewhere, the Benedictines closed it in the early 1960s. The monks removed to Conception Abbey, taking various items with them in the understanding that the land was being abandoned.\par
\par
The town was happy to see them gone, on the whole viewing anyone Catholic with a suspicious eye and monks were even worse, although there were never any problems.  In 1967 the order offered it to the Boy Scouts and again to the military.  They had hoped the army would keep it as a bombing range or other purposes that would force the army to keep it forever. Both said no.  The order kept the land until their lawyers found a clause that made the  land revert to the Muellers, who disputed it but were unwilling to take it to court. As church land, there had been no property taxes, but as private property there would be some.  The Muellers threatened to not pay the taxes and then the county would own it, but the county did not want it.  So the taxes were set to zero and the Muellers kept it, arguing among themselves what to do with it.  \par
 \par
\lang9 After the Benedictines left the gate did as well. The quarry became the unofficilal county  dumping ground for old appliances, refrigerators, cars, garbage and trash  on top of the burned debris. But all the copper and electrical wire, plumbing pipes and anything of value was stripped from the buildings, which, aside from the stone chapel and a few small ornamental stone walls, had been built poorly in war-time.  Nicholls teenagers would come and dare each other to get near the snakes in Snake Woods, as the one wooded ravine was named, sometimes fatally.  Trash, grafitti, and broken windows sped decay. Letters the County wrote the Muellers went unanswered; they were hoping the County would take the land. Erosion from the ever-present wind, which would search out and blow the last possible speck of dust from every crack and hole, set in and crept out from the desertified camp, leaving acres of exposed limestone that baked in July and August to over 120 degrees most days. In the winter it was windswept, and shallow pools would form that dried before algae had a chance. The limestone chapel baked in the summer heat.  With its pews, altar, all decoration, wood and window glass gone, it still had a strange beauty in the wilderness.  Some people went to see it, even after others with spray cans of paint had "decorated" it. \lang1033\par

